<subSubSection pageId="226" pageNumber="831" type="discussion">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zelebor" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1376,1601,3286,3320]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Rattus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="226" pageNumber="831" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="palmarum">Rattus palmarum</taxonomicName>
has not been included in any recent phylogenetic study, but it may be related to 
<taxonomicName box="[1533,1699,3326,3360]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Rattus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="226" pageNumber="831" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tiomanicus">R.tiomanicus</taxonomicName>
based on morphology and possibly 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. S. Miller" authorityYear="1902" box="[2208,2331,3326,3360]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="226" pageNumber="831" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="burrus">R. burrus</taxonomicName>
. Type locality was not given but was determined to be Car Nicobar based on detailed records of where specimens were collected. Monotypic.
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection box="[1375,2135,3452,3477]" pageId="226" pageNumber="831" type="multiple">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6888331" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6888331" box="[1375,2135,3452,3477]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6888331/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="226" pageNumber="831" startId="226.[1375,1547,3452,3477]" targetBox="[178,770,297,711]" targetPageId="227">
<paragraph blockId="226.[1375,2578,3078,3477]" box="[1375,2135,3452,3477]" pageId="226" pageNumber="831">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1375,1551,3452,3477]" pageId="226" pageNumber="831">Distribution.</emphasis>
Car Nicobar and Great Nicobar Is, India.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="227" pageNumber="832" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="227.[793,1384,287,715]" lastBlockId="227.[177,1387,721,1306]" pageId="227" pageNumber="832">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[793,1073,287,321]" pageId="227" pageNumber="832">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 225-240 mm, tail 220-231 mm, hindfoot 48 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Car Nicobar Rat is a large species of endemic and barely known 
<taxonomicName box="[899,984,485,519]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Rattus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="227" pageNumber="832" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Rattus</taxonomicName>
. Pelage is dense and rough. Dorsum is dark brown, mixed with longer black guard hairs and soft spines. Venter 1s white. Ears are dark brown; vibrissae are long. Tail is less than 100% of head-body length and unicolored dark brown. Skull is large and robust, with thick and high dorso-lateral ridges. There are five pairs of mammae: two axillary and three inguinal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="227" pageNumber="832" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="227.[177,1387,721,1306]" pageId="227" pageNumber="832">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[179,290,799,833]" pageId="227" pageNumber="832">Habitat.</emphasis>
Tropical evergreen forests and mangrove areas at elevations of 50-150 m. The Car Nicobar Rat might prefer crowns of palm trees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
